<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Associated Press; CLEANUP -- Workers sweep volcanic ash from the
tarmac at Manila International Airport on Wednesday to prepare for partial
operation. The airport is closed to incoming flights.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  VOLCANO; RESULT; US; MILITARY; TRIP  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  The U.S. Air Force decided today to withdraw more than 60 percent of its
personnel from the Philippines because of damage to Clark Air Base from the
Mount Pinatubo volcano.;    The decision to withdraw the bulk of the Air Force
personnel suggests that damage to Clark, where they had been stationed, is
extensive and that it may take months before the facility can be used.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  General News  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  VOLCANO CAUSES MORE TROOPS TO LEAVE  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Until today, the evacuation of Americans from the Philippines affected
primarily military dependents.;    Mount Pinatubo spewed more ash over Clark,
which is 10 miles away, and other areas during five eruptions today, and
regional officials raised the death toll from last week's massive explosions
to 227.;    Also today, all flights in and out of Manila's airport were
canceled for the day so workers could spread asphalt over tons of ash piled
along the runway shoulders.;    The U.S. evacuation announcement does not
affect Navy and Marine Corps personnel stationed at Subic Bay naval base 25
miles southwest of the volcano.;    U.S. Embassy spokesman Stanley Schrager
said 4,500 Air Force personnel will board ships Friday at Subic and travel
south to Cebu, where they will board flights for the United States.;    That
will leave 2,500 airmen in the Philippines -- 1,500 at Clark and another 1,000
at Subic.;    The 1,500 airmen at Clark were left behind to guard the base
when the other 15,000 American soldiers and their families evacuated to Subic
on June 10, a day after Mount Pinatubo began erupting, ending 600 years of
dormancy.;    The U.S. military announced on Sunday that Air Force family
members would be evacuated to the United States and then later expanded the
withdrawal to include families of Navy and defense department civilians as
well.  </TEXT>
