<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Associated Press; FLEEING TO SAFETY -- A U.S. soldier at Clark
Air Base directs Filipinos escaping volcanic ash rising behind them.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  PHILIPPINES; VOLCANO; PUBLIC; REACTION; UNUSUAL; WEATHER; CHANGE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Mount Pinatubo erupted today for a third straight day, shooting a cloud of gas
and steam more than 15 miles high, and an approaching typhoon threatened to
unleash tons of debris and boulders from the slopes of the rumbling volcano.; 
  Sirens blared at Clark Air Base, 10 miles east of Pinatubo, moments after
the volcano's latest eruption. Hundreds of U.S. troops milled about near the
gates, but no evacuation order was immediately issued.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  VOLCANO ERUPTS 3RD TIME
ONCOMING TYPHOON THREATENS MUDFLOWS  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Geologists said earlier today that new activity was imminent because
pressure was building inside the 4,795-foot volcano 60 miles north of the
capital, Manila.;    As though the volcano were not enough trouble, the Manila
weather bureau reported today that a typhoon was headed for the eastern coast
of Luzon island with maximum winds of 110 miles per hour. Typhoon Yunya is
expected to reach land late Saturday near Baler, about 90 miles northeast of
Mount Pinatubo. Rain already was falling today in Manila and Luzon.;    If the
typhoon brings more rain, scientists fear that it will unleash mudflows --
giant rivers of earth, boulders and debris fused with sticky volcanic ash.;   
Meanwhile, administration officials in Washington said Thursday that damage
from the volcano could cause the Bush administration to reduce or pull back
its offers for the continued use of the strategic U.S. military bases in the
Philippines.;    "If Clark Air Base is unuseful to us, they (Philippine
officials) will pay the price for their decision (to balk at recent U.S.
offers)," said an administration official, who has closely followed the
negotiations.;    At the moment, he said, the United States would not sign a
new agreement even if the Philippine government fully accepted the most recent
offer for the bases, the mainstay of U.S. military power in Southeast Asia.;  
 Rather, this official said, the United States wants to wait, at least
briefly, to see how much damage the volcano would cause to Clark and the Subic
Bay Naval Station. The eruption "could, in the extreme, render (Clark Air
Base) inoperative for jet aircraft," the administration official said.;    The
U.S. officials spoke on condition that they not be identified.;    This
spring, after a year of negotiations, the Bush administration and Philippine
officials had been moving toward an agreement that would permit continued U.S.
use of Clark and Subic Bay for at least seven more years. The current base
leases expire Sept. 16.;    However, at the end of the last round of talks in
May, the two sides still remained deadlocked on several issues.  </TEXT>
