<DESCRIPT>  VOLCANO; RESULT; US; MILITARY; FACILITY; PHILIPPINES  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  For generations, Clark Air Base and Subic Bay naval base were bastions of U.S.
power in Asia. After a week of volcanic eruptions, the bases are in ruins,
their future uncertain.;    Weeklong eruptions by Mount Pinatubo, 10 miles
west of Clark, dumped tons of ash on the two installations and rendered
airfields at both Clark and Subic's Cubi Point naval air station unusable.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  VOLCANO LEAVES BASES IN RUINS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  See also related article on page 12A of this section.
Additional information attached to the end of this article.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     For the first time since the Japanese occupation in World War II, the
United States has no operational military airfields in the Philippines,
although Cubi Point is expected to be back in service later this month.;   
The U.S. military last week evacuated about 15,000 troops and their families
from Clark to Subic and later decided to send the spouses and children of
fliers home until the volcano quiets.;    But damage during Saturday's
eruption was so extensive at Subic, 25 miles from the volcano, that it was
decided to send home all 20,000 dependents, including Navy families.;    The
evacuation is expected to be complete by the end of the week, drawing down the
size of the U.S. military community from about 35,000 a week ago to about
15,000 uniformed personnel.;    Confusion surrounding the eruptions diverted
attention from deadlocked talks on the future of the bases.;    The lease
expires on Sept. 16, and the talks on an extension bogged down over
compensation and how long the Americans can stay.;    "I don't have a sense at
this point where the negotiations are going," said a U.S. official, speaking
on condition of anonymity. "I don't think anybody else does either.";    The
United States had agreed to return four small facilities to the Philippines
this year but proposed a 10- to 12-year extension on Clark and Subic in return
for $360 million a year in compensation.;    Manila demanded $825 million a
year, half in cash and the rest in trade concessions and debt relief, in
return for a seven-year extension.;    The Philippines appeared to be wavering
on the "non-cash component" and the two sides were only about $30 million
apart when the volcano began erupting June 9.;    Publicly, both sides
maintain that the eruptions will have no effect on the talks. Foreign
Secretary Raul Manglapus, the chief Philippine negotiator, said it is up to
Washington to decide whether it no longer wants use of Clark.;    In fact,
however, Mount Pinatubo has cast a shadow over the entire bases issue. The
volcano has been relatively quiet since Saturday, but Raymundo Punongbayan,
director of the Philippine Institute of Vulcanology and Seismology, says it
may remain active for several years.;    That raises questions not only about
the feasibility of the Americans remaining there but also whether the
Philippines can implement plans to transform Clark into an international
airport and commercial center if the U.S. troops leave.;    The Philippines
has traditionally used the bases as leverage for extracting more aid from the
United States.;    As long as Mount Pinatubo remains a threat, however, Manila
finds itself in the same position as someone trying to sell a house on Love
Canal.;    "If he (Manglapus) had closed the deal a month ago, the Americans
would have laid down a fat check," said one diplomat, who refused to be
identified by name or nationality. "Nobody wants to commit himself to a large
compensation when he's facing a major reconstruction bill.";    There has been
no estimate of overall damage to the bases, but the figure could easily run
into the millions. Clark is covered by 10 to 12 inches of ash, and numerous
buildings have been damaged.;    Roads at Clark are clogged with ash and mud.
Water and power have been disrupted and there has been some theft, although
the extent is unclear.;    At Subic, tons of ash cover roofs, roads and harbor
facilities, and water and power have been disrupted.;    About 166 buildings
are damaged, including George Dewey High School, where a 9-year-old Air Force
dependent was killed when a roof caved in late Saturday.;    Hot lines set;
The Air Force, Navy and Marine Corps have established telephone hot lines for
information about U.S. armed services members their dependents in the
Philippines. Here are the toll-free telephone numbers:;    Air Force:
800-253-9276 (between 5 a.m. and 9 p.m. PDT).;    Navy: 800-255-3808 (24
hours).;    Marine Corps: 800-874-7454 (between 4:30 a.m. and 2 p.m. PDT).;   
Source: Associated Press  </TEXT>
