<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Associated Press; FOR SALE -- A woman in Manila, Philippines,
tries on a protective face mask being sold by a street vendor Tuesday.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  PHILIPPINES; VOLCANO; DISASTER; AID; LIST  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  An erupting volcano in the Philippines has turned the two largest U.S.
military bases in Asia into "a wasteland," U.S. Ambassador Nicholas Platt said
Tuesday.;    Platt, who has toured Subic Bay Naval Base and Clark Air Base
since the eruptions of Mount Pinatubo, said in a U.S. television interview
that it would be "a long time" before the full extent of the damage to the
bases was determined.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  HEAVY VOLCANIC DAMAGE AT BASES
CLARK, SUBIC SEEN AS 'A WASTELAND'  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     U.S. officials painted a depressing picture of conditions and damage at
Clark and Subic.;    At Subic, power and water have been virtually knocked out
by heavy ash falls, and at Clark the damage to buildings was more extensive
than initially thought, officials said. They said Clark's commissary and all
its warehouses collapsed under the weight of ash soaked by torrential rains,
and that many warehouses in the base's supply area also caved in.;    While
both bases have six to 12 inches of ash on the ground, Clark is in relatively
worse shape because it needs clean air to function as an air base, and the ash
fall has "rendered it inoperable," a U.S. diplomat said.;    Officials at
Subic Bay said it could be two months or more before full electricity and
water services were restored to the sprawling naval base.;    "From all the
ash, it looks like a moonscape up here," said Lt. Cmdr. Kevin Mukri, a
spokesman at Subic Bay.;    Scientists said the volcano was steadily calming
Tuesday, and they reduced the danger zone around Pinatubo from 18 miles to 12
miles. At least three small earth tremors were recorded at the volcano, and
one small explosion covered nearby Clark with fresh ash.;    Eight more U.S.
warships steamed toward Subic Bay to help speed an exodus of American military
dependents from Clark and the Subic naval base. Military officials hoped to
remove all 20,000 dependents by the end of the week.;    Since Sunday, 10
warships have carried more than 7,000 spouses and children from Subic.;    The
Red Cross said 146 people had died since June 9, when the 4,795-foot volcano
began spewing ash, steam and superheated rocks for the first time in 600
years. About 200,000 Filipinos were forced to flee their homes.;    Damage to
the two military sites has complicated already sensitive negotiations to renew
the base leases.;    "Everything's on hold right now," Pentagon spokesman Bob
Hall said after receiving damage reports on the two bases.;    "It's fair to
say that nobody right now is planning to start up negotiations on this issue
until both sides assess where they stand," Hall said.;     IF YOU'RE
