<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Associated Press; GROCERY DELIVERY -- Children push a vegetable
cart Thursday through ash-clogged streets of Olongapo, Philippines.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  PHILIPPINES; VOLCANO  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  The Air Force announced Thursday that it would evacuate more than half of its
uniformed personnel in the Philippines because of an erupting volcano that has
coated Clark Air Base in ash, making it unusable.;    The pullout of 4,500 of
the 7,000 active-duty workers assigned to Clark would be the first major
withdrawal of U.S. military personnel from the Philippines since Mount
Pinatubo unleashed a series of deadly eruptions last week. The evacuation of
their families was begun last week and is almost complete. Clark is 10 miles
east of the volcano.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  U.S. PLANS PULLOUT FROM CLARK
VOLCANO DRIVES 4,500 FROM BASE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Mercury News wire services contributed to this report.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The evacuation announced Thursday "was based on the conditions at Clark and
the inability of Clark to sustain a large population over the short term,"
said Stanley Schrager, spokesman for the U.S. Embassy in Manila. "It's a real
mess up there.";    U.S. officials in Washington and Manila have suggested
that Clark may be abandoned because of unacceptably high reconstruction costs.
Clark is buried under volcanic ash that varies from six inches to a foot
deep.;    Officials say the Subic Bay Naval Station is by far the more
valuable of the U.S. bases in the Philippines. It is a principal maintenance,
supply and storage base for the 180 ships of the Pacific Fleet, and is the
most convenient full-service port for Navy vessels in most areas of the Indian
Ocean.;    "Subic is a nearly perfect, well-protected deep-water harbor that
would be impossible for the Navy to re-create," said an administration
official in Washington. "Clark is not irreplaceable, especially if it's
covered with volcanic sludge.";    New eruptions Thursday released a cloud of
swirling gray ash nearly three miles high, dumping a new layer of ash on the
base and creating fresh misery for hundreds of thousands of Filipinos who have
struggled to dig out from beneath the ash and rock that rained down on their
homes last weekend.;    The death toll from last weekend's eruption rose to
268, Philippine officials said, and damage reports continue to grow. About
250,000 people were made homeless, and thousands of homes and buildings were
destroyed.  </TEXT>
