<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Paul Kitagaki Jr. -- Mercury News; Airman 1st Class Sean Taylor,
23, left the Philippines with only three days' worth of clothing. When Mount
Pinatubo blew, Taylor lost everything else, so he was applying for advance pay.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  US; MILITARY; CLOSING; PHILIPPINES; FACILITY; VOLCANO  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Airman 1st Class Sean Taylor stepped off a C-141 jet transport at Travis Air
Force Base Friday afternoon with all of his earthly belongings: two pairs of
Levis and four shirts stuffed into a black plastic bag.;    About three weeks
ago, after signs that the Mount Pinatubo volcano in the Philippines might
erupt, Taylor was sent from Clark Air Base to Subic Bay Naval Base to help set
up evacuation operations "just in case" Pinatubo blew.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  California News  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  VOLCANO EVACUEES ARRIVE
MOST FLED HOMES, LEFT BELONGINGS  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     "They told me to pack for three days, and that's what I did," said Taylor,
23. "Just 36 hours later, the volcano exploded and spewed ash everywhere. Next
thing you know, nobody's allowed to go back.";    He lost everything,
including his seven-foot pet python.;    For thousands of military personnel
like Taylor and their families, the journey home began June 10, when Mount
Pinatubo erupted for the first time, showering their homes at Clark Air Base
with ash.;    They left the base with nothing more than they could carry and
headed for Subic Bay, 23 miles south.;    After a second eruption five days
later, they were packed aboard U.S. Navy ships for a choppy 350-mile trip to
the island of Cebu, where Air Force and civilian aircraft flew them to Guam,
then to Hawaii, then to Travis.;    Four flights came in Thursday, another
four Friday, and up to 3,000 people were expected to pass through Travis by
Monday, said base spokesman Lt. Col. Jim Dilda.;    Other evacuees are being
flown to McChord Air Force Base in Washington. U.S. Embassy officials have
said between 6,000 to 8,000 family members will be flown to the United States
on chartered flights during the next few weeks.;    Looking exhausted and
anxious, more than 120 American service personnel and their spouses, children
and dogs and cats stumbled off the jet at 1:20 p.m. Friday at Travis.;    On
the runway, they were met by a Travis volunteer who acted as a "sponsor." Each
sponsor located a family and led them into the airport to be fed -- and in
some cases -- clothed. The volunteers played with children, walked dogs, and
set up travel arrangements for the displaced families with no money.;   
Eleven-year-old Jennifer Jettner sat with her sisters, Michelle, 18, and
Rizza, 17, while her mother waited in line for money -- they were able to get
as much as three months advance pay -- and plane tickets, so she and her
children could fly to Florida to stay with the girls' grandparents.;    The
girls talked of the terror of the volcano, saying the ash and smoke were so
thick at times it was impossible to see anything.;    "It was raining and
ashy, and it was pitch black," Jennifer said. "We had the ash falling,
tremors, and a typhoon all in one day.;    "One guy that was staying next door
to us did nothing but scream or sing really loud all day long," she said.
"Every time there was a tremor, he'd sing. I think he was praying or
something.";    He wasn't the only one.;    Taylor said he should have known
Pinatubo would blow in April when the enormous mountain began letting out
steam, a little at a time.;    But it wasn't until last week when that pitch
blackness hovered over Subic Bay for more than 27 hours that he thought,
"there's no way we can all get out of this alive.";    "The first time it
(erupted), it was beautiful," Taylor said. "It looked like a huge gray
mushroom cloud. Then the ash started falling.;    "Then it rained. And the ash
turned to cement," he said. "We were outside in the rain, on the tops of the
buildings, shoveling the ash off, hoping they wouldn't collapse beneath our
feet.;    "But all that's over now. And I'm on my way to Kansas City," he
said. "For some R and R."  </TEXT>
