<HEADLINE>  AIR BASE PERSONNEL TAKE A LONG, HOT DRIVE
TO SAFETY  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  See related story page 1A of this section.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     "We're gonna end up like refugees," fumed Air Force Staff Sgt. Lenny
Mastri, as he sat in a mileslong traffic jam with his wife and three children.
"I'd rather be back home. I'm not worried about the volcano.";    "When the
Air Force says move, we move," said Devata Rivard, whose husband was one of
1,500 U.S. troops left behind to guard America's oldest overseas base. "But I
believe the Lord will take care of us.";    U.S. Navy officials at Subic Bay
will need all the help they can get. The sudden evacuation from a feared
eruption of Mount Pinatubo has doubled Subic's resident population, a base
where housing already is in short supply.;    "We've asked all families to
double up," said Lt. Cmdr. Kevin Mukri, a Subic spokesman. "We're stuffing
people anywhere we can. . . . Basically, anywhere we can put a cot, we are."; 
  Some of the departing Clark personnel feared that "economic intruders,"
official Air Force jargon for local thieves, will take advantage of the
Americans' absence.;    "We took everything we wanted to see again," said a
burly Air Force sergeant whose red pickup truck was heavily loaded with bags
and boxes. "We live off-base. We think when we get back, everything will be
ripped off.";    A hand-lettered sign for Filipino workers, saying "No Work
Today," was tacked to the front gate at Clark after the last convoy of cars
left. Armed military police sped about inside in jeeps, but the sprawling base
otherwise appeared deserted.;    Not so outside, where some 350,000 residents
of Angeles City went about their lives.;    Philippine officials ordered more
than 12,000 Filipinos living near the volcano to leave the mountain, but they
did not evacuate Angeles City.;    City police Sgt. Rodolfo Talledo said most
residents were concerned about the volcano but there was no panic.;    "No one
seems to be afraid and nobody is evacuating because they don't think they are
in any immediate danger," he said. "Only the people from Clark left.";    The
departing Americans left behind a town of morose merchants, dispirited tavern
owners and idle bar girls at establishments with names like The Happy Hooker,
The Zoo and, perhaps a bit too apt these days, Earthquake McGoon's.;    Out on
the highway, one vendor did a brisk business selling icy soda pop to the long
line of departing Americans; another hawked bags of potato chips from under a
highway bridge. It seemed an odd start to what appears to be a long, uncertain
summer for tens of thousands of people forced from their homes by an angry
volcano.;    "The mountain's going to determine how long this is going to
last," said Kenneth West, an Air Force master sergeant stuck in a
non-air-conditioned car in the steamy traffic jam with his wife and four boys.  </TEXT>
